    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "thanks. log transformation makes sense for the price, but i'm also seeing some really extreme outliers in the residuals that are totally throwing off the fit. like, a few points are way off the charts compared to the rest of the distribution. is there a way to deal with those specific outliers without just deleting them?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Outliers, especially those that are truly extreme, are the bane of any linear model, as they can pull the regression line in a direction that doesn't represent the bulk of the data. You can't just toss them, though; you might want to try a more robust regression technique instead.\n\nInstead of standard Ordinary Least Squares (OLS), which is very sensitive to these big jumps, consider using **Robust Regression** methods. Techniques like **RANSAC** or **M-estimation** are designed to be less affected by those few, particularly nasty, outliers. These methods essentially give less weight to the points that are way off, allowing the main cluster of data to dictate the line.",
      "source": "target",
